ith the host not sending or processing ARP/replies properly.\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis\n- The most likely root cause is a host-side misconfiguration or transient link state issue on pc_0_1:\n  - Either the host has no default gateway configured (so it cannot send traffic to remote subnets), or\n  - The host's interface was administratively or operationally DOWN at times during the test (or flapping), causing it not to respond to or send traffic consistently.\n- Because the leaf router has an ARP entry for the host MAC and the BGP/RIBs are correct, core forwarding is functional; the asymmetry (leaf knows the host MAC, host has no ARP for the leaf and no route) points to pc_0_1 as the failure origin.\n\nRelevant evidence snippets (excerpts)\n- pc_0_0 ping -> pc_0_1: \"5 packets transmitted, 0 received, 100% packet loss\"\n- pc_0_1 ip_route: \"\" (empty) — no routes captured\n- pc_0_1 ip link (later): \"eth0: ... state UP LOWER_UP\" (inconsistent with earlier snapshot)\n- leaf_router_0_1 ip neigh: \"10.0.1.2 dev eth2 lladdr 2e:45:9b:34:61:67 STALE\"\n- BGP summaries: neighbors UP on all routers; each leaf shows 1 prefix received for the remote /24 and 2 prefixes total in neighbors listing — i.e., prefixes are being exchanged.\n\nAdditional notes and suggested next diagnostic checks (no remediation steps)\n- Verify pc_0_1's routing table while reproducing the ping (ip route show) to confirm whether the default gateway is missing at the time of the test.\n- On pc_0_1, check ARP and link state concurrently:\n  - ip neigh show\n  - ip addr show dev eth0\n  - ip link show eth0\n  - dmesg or syslog for NIC or link flaps\n- From leaf_router_0_1, capture traffic (tcpdump on eth2) while pinging from pc_0_0 to see whether the ICMP echo request reaches the host and whether an ICMP echo-reply is generated by the host.\n- On pc_0_1, check for local firewall rules (iptables/nftables) which might drop ICMP or interfere with ARP (if any).\n- Repeat the ping test both directions (pc_0_1